It took Japan less than half a century to rise to power and become a major world player. In the last}{ }{\fs22 quarter of the 19th century, Japan turned to Western technology in order to avoid the fate of China,}{ }{\fs22 
namelyWestern dominance. By the 1890s, Japan had so far modernized and strengthened itself that}{ }{\fs22 it was able to join in the scramble for possessions in China. In 1902, it signed a treaty with Great}{ }{\fs22 
Britain which recognized its new status among other things. At the end of the First World War,}{ }{\fs22 Japan was invited as one of the winning powers, to participate in the Peace Conference. In reality,}{ }{\fs22 
however, the Japanese found that they were not considered equal to the Europeans and the}{ }{\fs22 Americans. This Western hypocrisy caused Japan to lose faith in the Western powers and pursue a}{ }{\fs22 
pan-Asian order, with Japan as its leader. In order to become self-sufficient, Japan needed the raw}{ }{\fs22 materials of East Asia, as well as "living-space" for its surplus population. This pan-Asian vision}{ }{\fs22 
threatened European and American interests in the region, which therefore opposed it. Japan found}{ }{\fs22 itself by the 1930s with a choice:-to confront the Western powers, especially the United States, and}{ }{\fs22 
thereby risk war, or to retreat and accept humiliation and a loss of power. This essay is going to}{ }{\fs22 examine how Japan reached that position by the 1930s and how it made the choice for war. I am}{ }{\fs22 
going to argue that Japan's policies were shaped more by fear and a feeling of weakness, than by a}{ }{\fs22 confidence in its own military strength and its racial superiority, which has been the more accepted}{ }{\fs22 view among historians.}{
